When you install PyTorch like this:

pip install torch torchvision torchaudio --index-url https://download.pytorch.org/whl/cu121

NVIDIA cuDNN is usually bundled inside PyTorch, so there is often no separate “cuDNN install” to check in the traditional sense.

Instead, you verify it indirectly through PyTorch.

🧠 How to check if cuDNN is working (correct way)

Run Python:

import torch

print("CUDA available:", torch.cuda.is_available())
print("GPU:", torch.cuda.get_device_name(0))
print("cuDNN version:", torch.backends.cudnn.version())
print("cuDNN enabled:", torch.backends.cudnn.enabled)
🔍 How to interpret results
✅ Good (cuDNN working)

You should see something like:

CUDA available: True
GPU name: RTX A400
cuDNN version: 8902 (or similar)
cuDNN enabled: True
❌ If cuDNN is NOT working

You might see:

cuDNN version: None
or errors like CUDA not available

That means:

wrong PyTorch build
or broken CUDA environment
🧠 Important insight (your system)

Because you installed:

CUDA Toolkit 12.5 ✔
Driver 580 ✔
PyTorch cu121 build ✔ (after install)

👉 cuDNN will NOT appear as a separate system package

Instead:

It is embedded inside PyTorch’s CUDA runtime.

⚠️ Common misunderstanding

People often try:

dpkg -l | grep cudnn

That only works if you installed system cuDNN manually.

But with modern PyTorch:

❌ No system cuDNN needed
✔ It lives inside the Python wheel

🚀 Quick full test (recommended)

After installing PyTorch, run:

import torch

x = torch.randn(1000, 1000).cuda()
y = torch.mm(x, x)

print("GPU computation OK")

If this runs:

CUDA ✔
cuDNN ✔
GPU pipeline ✔
🧭 Bottom line

To check cuDNN:

✔ Don’t look for system packages
✔ Don’t rely on apt/dpkg
✔ Use:

torch.backends.cudnn.version()

That is the real indicator in modern AI stacks.


